title: For Sale/Trade:  .308 scout/sniper/hunting package.
postcontent:
This is a complete setup capable of anything from 10-1,000 yards. Round count is around 120. I don't use it as much as I thought I would. It is easily capable of sub-moa groups. I'm sure it could be dialed in even better with hand-loads. 

Includes: 
-Savage Hog hunter rifle
-SWFA SS 6x42 mil/mil scope
-Sunshade
-Butler creek scope caps
-Weaver 20 moa scope base
-A2 style .308 flash hider and lock nut
-Harris lightweight 9-13" bipod
-Sling
-Cheek rest
-160 rounds of 180 gr. federal fusion
-190 rounds of Fiocchi 180 gr. soft points
-40 rounds of 180 gr Winchester soft points
-40 rounds of Herter's 150 gr fmj (I haven't shot any of these through this rifle, but I have them)   


This setup has been put together and maintained with extreme care. All screws have been torqued down evenly and blue locktite was used. The scope, base and level have been checked and are perfectly level.  

The 6x42 SWFA scope is a very tough and reliable with excellent light transmission. It is the 6x version of a military 10x scope. I prefer the 6x for the wider field of view and adequate magnification out to any distance that the .308 is still useful.

The savage hog hunter is a great, handy platform with an excellent trigger. It features a medium profile barrel and a tight 1/10 twist rate that does well with heavier projectiles.     

I put this together to be a sort of middle ground between a scout rifle and a sniper rifle. It can do anything you would want a bolt gun to do out to 1000 yards. 

This setup would run about $1450 to put together (including the ammo).
I'm asking $1,150 cash or $1,250 trade value. 

I may concider selling the rifle and the ammo seperatly. Just ask. 

Buyer must be legally allowed to own long guns in MN.

title: For Sale:  7.62x54 Ammo - 120 Round Assortment - Hard to Find Stuff
postcontent:
Here an assortment of 7.62x54 ammo that I've accumulated over many years.

None of this ammo is easy to find anymore:   

40 rounds Hungarian Silver/Yellow tip. This ammo has a 182 grain steel core bullet.    
It hits much harder than the light ball that's currently available, and it penetrates like crazy.   
It also shoots a good deal more accurately in my Mosins.   

40 rounds Russian 7N1 Sniper. This ammo was developed by the Russian Military to have a much more accurate round for their snipers. Ammo loaded with a special 152 grain FMJ boat tail bullet. Bullet has a steel core, then an empty air space followed by a lead knocker in the base. Upon impact the lead knocker moves forward destabilizing the bullet causing a very severe wound. This ammo shoots significantly tighter groups in all my rifles including the bolt actions. The paper outer wrapper is stamped with the Cyrillic word for Sniper.   

20 rounds East German M39 ammo. This ammo has an all black color 124 grain steel jacketed, steel core bullet. It was originally designed as practice ammo for their machine guns. The concept was that the lighter bullet would travel less far. It is however a full power round and will penetrate 1/4" steel plate at 100 yards. Recoil is greatly reduced due to the lighter bullet making it perfect for anyone who is sensitive to recoil.    

20 rounds Bulgarian brass case with a 149 grain magnetic bullet. Ammo is from the mid 50's but looks like it was made yesterday. It's super clean ammo and I've always felt brass cased ammo operated more smoothly than the steel case stuff.   

$100 picked up in the Brandon area. Buyer must be at least 18 to purchase this ammo. I can ship this vis UPS ground at buyers expense.
